folder: East End Avenue & 88th Street (East), Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Carl Schurz Park: A view of the northern end of the park, showing the Gracie Mansion there in. This photograph was taken from East End Ave., at East 88th Street and shows the east side of the afore mentioned
Ave. in the foreground.
January 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
A similar view, showing mainly the south side of the Mansion. The portion appearing on the right, faces the East River.
January 31, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
(3)
The same as No. 2, at a later date. Appearing in the background are two bridges over the East River; the curved span of the Hellgate;
and the suspension type, the Triborough.
March 29, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

The mansion was made the official residence of the Mayor of the City of New York on January 8, 1942 by an act of the Board of Estimate.
See "The New York Times," January 9, 1942

folder: East End Avenue & 88th Street (East), Manhattan, NY
text:
GRACIE MANSI0N East End Avenue and East 88th Street, Manhattan. Built in the Federal style about 1799 on the site of a revolutionary fort, it was the country home of Archibald Gracie, shipping merchant and a director of The Bank of New York. The house was completely restored in 1927, and until 1932 it housed the Museum of the City of New York. It became the official mayor's residence in 1942 during Fiorello LaGuardia's third term.
Bank of New York Calendar 1967-68
